---
// older adults + sleep aids — CONTEXT page (CHK-5.2, PR-B). NOT a graded remedy and NOT advice about
// what to take: it's context on why the stakes of any sleep aid are HIGHER in later life (next-day
// falls/impairment, slower drug clearance, anticholinergic load) and why the decision belongs with a
// clinician or pharmacist. No tier badge, no evidence-gate chips, no plannedTier. Mirrors
// medications-and-sleep-aids.astro / melatonin-gummies.astro structure exactly. Every specific is cited
// to a source verified firsthand:
//   1 AGS Beers Criteria 2023 (J Am Geriatr Soc 2023;71(7):2052–2081) — read the primary table firsthand:
//     first-generation antihistamines (incl. diphenhydramine PO, doxylamine — the sedating ingredients in
//     OTC "PM" products) are recommendation "Avoid" in older adults: highly anticholinergic, clearance
//     reduced with age, tolerance develops as a hypnotic, cumulative anticholinergic exposure linked to
//     falls/delirium/dementia. PMID 37139824.
//   2 Glass BMJ 2005 — meta-analysis of 24 RCTs in adults ≥60: small sleep gain (~25 min) vs clear harm;
//     NNT 13, NNH 6; cognitive events ~4.78x, psychomotor ~2.61x more common than placebo. PMID 16284208.
//   3 Zhdanova 2001 (reused from melatonin corpus) — a LOW physiological 0.3 mg dose restored sleep
//     efficiency in age-related insomnia; higher doses brought side effects. PMID 11600532 (verified).
//   4 Culpepper & Wingertzahn 2015 (reused from /medications-and-sleep-aids) — diphenhydramine/doxylamine
//     are H1 antihistamines with anticholinergic effects + next-day psychomotor impairment. PMID 27057416.
// Shift-work-disorder / prescription-hypnotic specifics stay routed to a clinician — no directive to
// start or stop anything appears here.
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import ContextBanner from '../components/ContextBanner.astro';
import ContextSources from '../components/ContextSources.astro';
import Disclaimer from '../components/Disclaimer.astro';
import Fn from '../components/Fn.astro';

const sources = [
  {
    n: 1,
    cite: 'By the 2023 American Geriatrics Society Beers Criteria® Update Expert Panel. American Geriatrics Society 2023 updated AGS Beers Criteria® for potentially inappropriate medication use in older adults. J Am Geriatr Soc. 2023;71(7):2052–2081.',
    finding:
      'the standard geriatric-prescribing reference lists first-generation antihistamines — including the diphenhydramine and doxylamine inside most OTC “PM” sleep products — with a recommendation to AVOID in older adults (moderate quality of evidence, strong recommendation): they are highly anticholinergic, clearance falls with advanced age, tolerance to the sleep effect develops when used as a hypnotic, and cumulative anticholinergic exposure is associated with an increased risk of falls, delirium, and dementia.',
    pmid: '37139824',
    doi: '10.1111/jgs.18372',
  },
  {
    n: 2,
    cite: 'Glass J, Lanctôt KL, Herrmann N, Sproule BA, Busto UE. Sedative hypnotics in older people with insomnia: meta-analysis of risks and benefits. BMJ. 2005;331(7526):1169.',
    finding:
      'meta-analysis of 24 randomised trials (2,417 participants aged 60+): sedative hypnotics improved sleep only modestly (about 25 minutes of extra sleep) while adverse events were common — the number needed to harm for any adverse event was 6 (95% CI 4.7–7.1) against a number needed to treat for improved sleep of 13, with cognitive events roughly 4.78 times and psychomotor events roughly 2.61 times more common than placebo; the authors concluded the benefits may not justify the risks in older people.',
    pmid: '16284208',
  },
  {
    n: 3,
    cite: 'Zhdanova IV, Wurtman RJ, Regan MM, Taylor JA, Shi JP, Leclair OU. Melatonin treatment for age-related insomnia. J Clin Endocrinol Metab. 2001;86(10):4727–4730.',
    finding:
      'in older adults with insomnia, a low physiological dose of 0.3 mg melatonin restored sleep efficiency (P < 0.0001) and returned nighttime plasma melatonin to normal levels, whereas a higher pharmacological dose produced side effects such as lowered body temperature — the studied dose in this group was small, not large.',
    pmid: '11600532',
  },
  {
    n: 4,
    cite: 'Culpepper L, Wingertzahn MA. Over-the-Counter Agents for the Treatment of Occasional Disturbed Sleep or Transient Insomnia: A Systematic Review of Efficacy and Safety. Prim Care Companion CNS Disord. 2015;17(6):10.4088/PCC.15r01798.',
    finding:
      'systematic review of OTC sleep agents: the antihistamines diphenhydramine and doxylamine are nonselective H1 antagonists whose sedation comes with anticholinergic effects (dry mouth, blurred vision) and documented next-day psychomotor impairment, with limited and inconsistent efficacy evidence.',
    pmid: '27057416',
    doi: '10.4088/PCC.15r01798',
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="older adults + sleep aids: why the stakes are higher | Somnary"
  description="sleep changes with age, and so do the stakes of a sleep aid: the same drowsiness that helps at night is tied to next-day falls and impaired thinking, and the antihistamines in common OTC 'PM' products are flagged specifically for older adults. context on why a sleep aid in later life is a clinician conversation — not a grade, and not advice about what to take."
  canonical="https://somnary.vercel.app/older-adults"
>
  <main class="page">
    <header class="head">
      <p class="eyebrow">context · older adults</p>
      <h1 class="title">Older adults + sleep aids</h1>
      <p class="dek">
        Sleep changes with age, and so do the stakes of anything taken for it. The same drowsiness
        that helps at night doesn't always clear by morning — and in later life next-day sedation is
        tied to falls and foggy thinking. Some of the most common over-the-counter &ldquo;PM&rdquo;
        sleep products are flagged <em>specifically</em> for older adults. This page is context on why
        a sleep aid in later life belongs in a conversation with a clinician or pharmacist — it is not
        a grade, and it does not tell you what to take or what is safe for you.
      </p>
    </header>

    <ContextBanner
      note="whether a sleep aid fits later in life depends on your other medicines, your kidney and liver function, and your fall risk — a clinical question, not one a wiki can settle. this page describes what the evidence and geriatric guidelines document, and routes it to a clinician."
    />

    <p class="who">
      <span class="who-tag">who this is for</span>
      adults roughly 65 and older who are weighing a sleep aid — and the family members or carers
      helping them decide — especially anyone already taking other medicines or with a history of
      falls or unsteadiness.
    </p>

    <!-- safety boundary: next-day falls/impairment + anticholinergic load in later life (serious) -->
    <section class="callout sev-serious" role="note" aria-label="older-adult sleep-aid hazard">
      <div class="callout-head">
        <span class="sigil" aria-hidden="true">!</span>
        <p class="callout-title">In later life, a sleep aid's next-day fog can become a fall</p>
      </div>
      <p class="callout-body">
        The drowsiness that helps at night doesn't always clear by morning, and in older adults
        next-day sedation is tied to <strong>falls</strong> and impaired thinking. The antihistamines
        that do the sedating in most OTC &ldquo;PM&rdquo; products — diphenhydramine and doxylamine —
        are listed in the 2023 AGS Beers Criteria as potentially inappropriate in older adults, with a
        recommendation to <strong>avoid</strong>: they are highly anticholinergic, and cumulative
        anticholinergic use is linked to falls, delirium, and dementia.<Fn n={1} /> Prescription
        sedative sleeping pills carry their own raised risk of harm in this age group,<Fn n={2} /> and
        those antihistamines add next-day psychomotor impairment on their own.<Fn n={4} /> None of this
        tells you what is safe for you. Whether any sleep aid fits belongs with a clinician or
        pharmacist who can see your full medication list and fall risk — before you start. A new or
        worsening sleep problem in later life can itself signal something that needs
        <a href="/when-to-see-a-doctor">evaluation</a>, not a supplement.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- section 01: what people assume -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 01</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">What people assume</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          OTC &ldquo;PM&rdquo; products and &ldquo;natural&rdquo; sleep aids read as a mild, low-stakes
          way to handle a restless night, and the quiet assumption is that whatever is fine for a
          younger adult is fine at any age. In later life that assumption is exactly where the trouble
          starts: the body clears these ingredients more slowly, the structure of sleep itself changes,
          and the margin between &ldquo;helps me sleep&rdquo; and &ldquo;leaves me unsteady
          tomorrow&rdquo; narrows. The through-line of this page is that age raises the stakes of the
          same product — which is why the decision moves from a shelf to a clinician.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 02: what's actually documented -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 02</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">What's actually documented</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Geriatric prescribing guidance is specific here. The 2023 AGS Beers Criteria — the standard
          reference for medications that are potentially inappropriate in older adults — lists
          first-generation antihistamines, including the diphenhydramine and doxylamine inside most OTC
          &ldquo;PM&rdquo; products, with a recommendation to <strong>avoid</strong>: they are highly
          anticholinergic, their clearance falls with age, tolerance to the sleep effect develops, and
          cumulative anticholinergic exposure is associated with <strong>falls, delirium, and
          dementia</strong>.<Fn n={1} /> A separate systematic review found those same antihistamines
          also carry next-day psychomotor impairment.<Fn n={4} />
        </p>
        <p>
          Prescription sedative sleeping pills don't escape this either. A <em>BMJ</em> meta-analysis
          of 24 trials in adults over 60 found only a small sleep benefit — roughly
          <strong>25 extra minutes</strong> — against clearly higher harm: the number needed to harm
          for any adverse event was <strong>6</strong>, against a number needed to treat of 13, with
          cognitive events about <strong>4.78 times</strong> and psychomotor events about
          <strong>2.61 times</strong> more common than placebo; the authors concluded the benefits may
          not justify the risks in older people.<Fn n={2} /> Melatonin sits differently: the trial most
          cited in this group used a low physiological dose of <strong>0.3 mg</strong>, which restored
          sleep efficiency and returned nighttime melatonin to normal, while a higher dose brought side
          effects<Fn n={3} /> — a reminder that in older adults the amount studied was small.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 03: what these findings do NOT show -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 03</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">What these findings do <em>not</em> show</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          These are population-level cautions and averages, not a verdict on you. Beers flags a class
          as <em>potentially</em> inappropriate — that word is doing real work: it means review and
          caution, not an absolute ban for every person.<Fn n={1} /> The sedative-hypnotic harms are
          averages across trials, not a prediction for one individual,<Fn n={2} /> and the 0.3 mg
          melatonin result is a single small study of sleep efficiency, not evidence of a safe
          long-term dose or a reason to start.<Fn n={3} /> None of this can diagnose why sleep changed,
          rank one option against another for your health, or replace a clinician who can weigh your
          kidneys, liver, other medicines, and fall history. The honest takeaway is narrow: the stakes
          are higher with age, so the decision belongs with a professional.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 04: dose / label / timing reality -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 04</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">Dose, label &amp; timing reality</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The number on a box was not set with an older adult's slower drug clearance in mind, and OTC
          &ldquo;PM&rdquo; labels don't flag the anticholinergic load they add to medicines already in
          the cabinet.<Fn n={1} /><Fn n={4} /> Where melatonin has been studied in older adults, the
          doses were low and physiological — the 0.3 mg used in the age-related insomnia trial is far
          below the 5 or 10 mg common on shelves.<Fn n={3} /> This page describes what the studies
          used; it does not tell you what to take. A pharmacist can check any ingredient against your
          full list in minutes, and <a href="/melatonin-dose-timing">melatonin dose &amp; timing</a>
          covers what the trials actually used. What fits <em>your</em> body and regimen is a question
          only a clinician or pharmacist with the whole picture can answer — not a label, and not this
          page.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 05: take these to a clinician or pharmacist -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 05</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">Take these to a clinician or pharmacist</h2>
      <ul class="ask">
        <li>here is my full medication list — does this sleep aid, or the antihistamine in this &ldquo;PM&rdquo; product, appear on the Beers list or interact with anything I take?</li>
        <li>given any history of falls or unsteadiness, could this raise my risk overnight or the next morning?</li>
        <li>do my kidney or liver function, or my age, change how long this stays in my system?</li>
        <li>if melatonin is considered at all, what low dose and form have actually been studied in older adults?</li>
        <li>has my sleep changed enough that it should be evaluated, rather than managed with a sleep aid?</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- related: the primary boundary + the interaction context + the graded hub + tools -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">related</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">Read next</h2>
      <ul class="related">
        <li><a href="/safety">safety &amp; interactions</a> — the primary boundary: how Somnary handles interactions and when to route to a clinician.</li>
        <li><a href="/medications-and-sleep-aids">medications &amp; sleep aids</a> — why interactions and timing are a pharmacist conversation before any sleep aid.</li>
        <li><a href="/when-to-see-a-doctor">when to see a doctor</a> — the signs that a sleep change needs evaluation, not a supplement.</li>
        <li><a href="/r/melatonin">melatonin</a> — the full evidence grade and what the trials found.</li>
        <li><a href="/melatonin-dose-timing">melatonin dose &amp; timing</a> — how much, and when, the studies actually used.</li>
        <li><a href="/r/cbt-i">CBT-I</a> — the non-drug approach to chronic insomnia, especially relevant when sleep-aid risks run higher.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <ContextSources sources={sources} />

    <div class="disclaimer-slot">
      <Disclaimer variant="standard" />
    </div>

    <p class="review-line">
      reviewed 2026-07-08 · found an error? <a href="/methodology#corrections">corrections →</a>
    </p>
  </main>
</Base>

